The time independant Schrödinger equationThe hydrogen atom is constituted of two particles, one proton and one electron. As we want to solve it using quantum mechanics, we will need to use the Schrödinger equation egin{equation}	\label{eq:sch}	\hat{H} \Psi(\vec{r}) = E \Psi(\vec{r})\end{equation}In \eqref{eq:sch} the \( \hat{H} \) is the Hamiltonian of the system and can be expressed as the sum of three operators. egin{equation}	\label{eq:operators}	\hat{H} = \hat{T}_{e} + \hat{T}_{p} + \hat{V}\end{equation}Where \( \hat{T} \) is the kinetic energy operator, we can modify the kinetic energy operators to have only one operator depending on the reduced mass of the system \( \mu =  rac{m_em_p}{m_e+m_p} \) egin{align}	\hat{T}_E + \hat{T}_p &amp;= - rac{\hbar}{2m_{e}} 
abla^2 -  rac{\hbar}{2m_{p}} 
abla^2 \ &amp;= - rac{\hbar}{2} \left[  rac{1}{m_e} +  rac{1}{m_p} ight] 
abla^2 \		&amp;= - rac{\hbar}{2}  rac{m_e + m_p}{m_em_p} 
abla^2 \		&amp;= -  rac{\hbar}{2 \mu}
abla^2\end{align}And \( \hat{V} \) is the potential operator, here we will study free hydrogen atom, so the only potential is the potential of the proton on the neutron which is described by a Coulomb potential. egin{equation}	\label{eq:coulomb}	\hat{V} = -  rac{Ze^2}{4 \pi \varepsilon_0 r}\end{equation}In \eqref{eq:coulomb} the \( Z \) is the charge of the nucleus, 1 for the Hydrogen atom, $e$ is the elementary charge (\( e = 1.602176634 	imes 10^{-19}\) C),\( \varepsilon_0 \) is the vacuum permittivity (\( \varepsilon_0 = 8.8541878128 	imes 10^{-12} \) F.m\(^{-1}\) ) and \(r\) is the distance between the electron and the proton.\eqref{eq:sch} can then be rewritten for this system egin{equation}	\label{eq:sch2}	\left[ -  rac{\hbar}{2\mu}
abla^2 -  rac{e^2}{4\pi \varepsilon_0 r} - E ight] \Psi(\vec{r}) = 0\end{equation}\( 
abla^2 \) is the Laplacian operator, in spherical coordinates it is \eqref{eq:laplacian} egin{equation}	\label{eq:laplacian}	
abla^2 =  rac{1}{r^2}  rac{\partial}{\partial r} \left( r^2  rac{\partial}{\partial r} ight) +  rac{1}{r^2 \sin 	heta}  rac{\partial}{\partial 	heta} \left( \sin 	heta  rac{\partial}{\partial 	heta} ight) +  rac{1}{r^2 \sin^2 	heta}  rac{\partial^2}{\partial \Phi^2}\end{equation}\( \Psi(\vec{r}) \) is the wavefunction of the system, and \( |\Psi(\vec{r})|^2 \) is the probability of finding the electron at the position \( \vec{r} \) (when the origin is the position of the nucleus). This means that the wavefunction needs to be normalized \eqref{eq:normalized} egin{equation}	\label{eq:normalized}	\int_{0}^{+\infty}\int_{0}^{\pi}\int_{0}^{2 \pi} |\Psi(r,	heta,\phi)|^2 r^2 \cos 	heta dr d	heta d\phi = 1\end{equation}We can now mix \eqref{eq:laplacian} with \eqref{eq:sch2}, we have \eqref{eq:sch3} egin{equation}	\scriptsize{	\label{eq:sch3}	 -  rac{\hbar}{2\mu} \left[ rac{1}{r^2}  rac{\partial }{\partial r} \left( r^2  rac{\partial \Psi(r,	heta,\phi)}{\partial r} ight) +  rac{1}{r^2 \sin 	heta}  rac{\partial}{\partial 	heta} \left( \sin 	heta  rac{\partial\Psi(r,	heta,\phi)}{\partial 	heta} ight) +  rac{1}{r^2 \sin^2 	heta}  rac{\partial^2\Psi(r,	heta,\phi)}{\partial \phi^2} ight] -  rac{e^2}{4\pi \varepsilon_0 r}\Psi(r,	heta,\phi) - E \Psi(r,	heta,\phi) = 0}\end{equation}We can now drop the minus sign, multiply by \(  rac{2\mu}{\hbar^2} \) and factorize the two last term by \( \Psi(r,	heta,\phi) \) egin{equation}\scriptsize{	\label{eq:sch4}	  rac{1}{r^2}  rac{\partial }{\partial r} \left( r^2  rac{\partial \Psi(r,	heta,\phi)}{\partial r} ight) +  rac{1}{r^2 \sin 	heta}  rac{\partial}{\partial 	heta} \left( \sin 	heta  rac{\partial\Psi(r,	heta,\phi)}{\partial 	heta} ight) +  rac{1}{r^2 \sin^2 	heta}  rac{\partial^2\Psi(r,	heta,\phi)}{\partial \phi^2}  +  rac{2\mu}{\hbar^2}\left(  rac{e^2}{4\pi \varepsilon_0 r} + E ight) \Psi(r,	heta,\phi) = 0}\end{equation}Separation of variablesLet’s assume that \( \Psi(r, 	heta, \phi) \) is the product of two functions, one that only depends on \( r \) and the other that only depends on \( 	heta \) and \( \phi \) egin{equation}	\label{eq:psi}	\Psi(r,	heta,\phi) = R(r)Y(	heta,\phi)\end{equation}It is now possible to plug \eqref{eq:psi} in \eqref{eq:sch4} and rearrange a bit. egin{align}	 \scriptsize{ rac{Y(	heta,\phi)}{r^2}  rac{\partial }{\partial r} \left( r^2  rac{\partial R(r)}{\partial r} ight) +  rac{R(r)}{r^2 \sin 	heta}  rac{\partial}{\partial 	heta} \left( \sin 	heta  rac{\partial Y(	heta,\phi)}{\partial 	heta} ight) +  rac{R(r)}{r^2 \sin^2 	heta}  rac{\partial^2Y(	heta,\phi)}{\partial \phi^2} +  rac{2\mu}{\hbar^2} \left( rac{e^2}{4\pi \varepsilon_0 r} + E ight) R(r) Y(	heta,\phi)}&amp;= 0 \\label{eq:sch5}	 \scriptsize{\color{#235FA4}{ rac{1}{R(r)}  rac{\partial }{\partial r} \left( r^2  rac{\partial R(r)}{\partial r} ight)+  rac{2\mu r^2}{\hbar^2} \left( rac{e^2}{4\pi \varepsilon_0 r} + E ight)}} +\color{#FF4242}{  rac{1}{Y(	heta,\phi) \sin 	heta}  rac{\partial}{\partial 	heta} \left( \sin 	heta  rac{\partial Y(	heta,\phi)}{\partial 	heta} ight) +  rac{1}{Y(\phi,	heta) \sin^2 	heta}  rac{\partial^2Y(	heta,\phi)}{\partial \phi^2}} &amp;= 0\end{align}In \eqref{eq:sch5} there are two different part, one that only depends on \( r \) (blue) and the other that depends on $	heta$ and \( \phi \) (red). It is then possible to separate this equation in two equation, the radial equation (that depends only on \( r \)) and the angular equation (that depends on \( \phi \) and \( 	heta \) ), where \( A \) is a constant. egin{align}	\label{eq:radial}	 rac{d}{d r} \left(r^2  rac{d R(r)}{d r} ight) +  rac{2\mu r^2}{\hbar^2} \left(  rac{e^2}{4\pi\varepsilon r} + E ight)R(r) - AR(r) &amp;= 0 \	\label{eq:polar}	 rac{1}{\sin 	heta}  rac{\partial}{\partial 	heta} \left(\sin 	heta  rac{\partial Y(	heta,\phi)}{\partial 	heta}ight) +  rac{1}{\sin^2 	heta}  rac{\partial^2 Y(	heta,\phi)}{\partial \phi^2} + AY(	heta,\phi) &amp;= 0\end{align}The polar equationThe polar equation \eqref{eq:polar} can be separated again, assuming that \( Y(	heta,\phi) \) is the product of two independant functions of \( 	heta \) and \( \phi \) egin{equation}	\label{eq:sepolar}	Y(	heta,\phi) = \Theta(	heta)\Phi(\phi)\end{equation}\eqref{eq:sepolar} can be inserted in \eqref{eq:polar} which gives \eqref{eq:seppolar} egin{align}	 rac{\Phi(\phi)}{\sin 	heta}  rac{d}{d	heta} \left(\sin 	heta  rac{d\Theta(	heta)}{d 	heta} ight) +  rac{\Theta(	heta)}{\sin^2 	heta}  rac{d^2 \Phi(\phi)}{d \phi^2} + A \Theta(	heta) \Phi(\phi) &amp;= 0 \	\label{eq:seppolar}	\color{#6FDE64}{ rac{\sin 	heta}{\Theta(	heta)}  rac{d}{d	heta}\left(\sin 	heta  rac{d \Theta(	heta)}{d 	heta} ight)} + \color{#FF934F}{ rac{1}{\Phi(\phi)}  rac{d^2 \Phi(\phi)}{d\Phi^2}} + \color{#6FDE64}{A  \sin^2 	heta} &amp;= 0 \\end{align}In \eqref{eq:seppolar} we can see that there are two different parts, one depending only on $\phi$ and the other depending only on $	heta$. egin{align}	\label{eq:azimuth}	 rac{d^2 \Phi(\phi)}{d \phi^2} + B \Phi(\phi) &amp;= 0 \	\label{eq:plar}	\sin 	heta  rac{d}{d	heta}\left( \sin 	heta  rac{d \Theta(	heta)}{d 	heta} ight) + A\sin 	heta - B \Theta(	heta) &amp;= 0\end{align}\eqref{eq:azimuth} is called the Azimuthal equation, as \( \phi \) descibe the elevation to the plane \( xOy \), and \eqref{eq:plar} is called the Polar equation as \( 	heta \) describe the polar angle in the plane \( xOy \)The Azimuthal equationThe Azimuthal equation \label{eq:azimuth} is a second order differential equation with constant coefficient so its solutions are simply \eqref{eq:azsol} egin{equation}	\label{eq:azsol}	\Phi(\phi) = \alpha e^{im\phi} +  eta e^{-im\phi}\end{equation}With \( B = m^2\) , m needs to be an integer because \( \Phi(2\pi) = \Phi(0) \) . We can conveniently decide to set \(  eta \) to 0, which gives \eqref{eq:azisol} egin{equation}	\label{eq:azisol}	\Phi(\phi) = \alpha e^{im\phi}\end{equation}The Polar equationWe can use the fact that \( B = m^2 \) to rewrite and rearrange the Polar equation as \eqref{eq:plar2} egin{equation}	\label{eq:plar2}	 rac{1}{\sin 	heta}  rac{d}{d	heta}\left( \sin 	heta  rac{d \Theta(	heta)}{d 	heta} ight) + \Theta(	heta)\left(A -  rac{m^2}{\sin^2 	heta} ight) = 0\end{equation}We will now need to use a change of variables. We will express this equation as a function of \( \cos 	heta \). \( P(\cos 	heta) = \Theta(	heta)\), we have \(  rac{d}{d 	heta} =  rac{d \cos 	heta}{d 	heta}  rac{d}{d\cos 	heta} = -\sin 	heta  rac{d}{d \cos 	heta} \). Using that, we have \eqref{eq:change1}. egin{align}	 rac{1}{\sin 	heta}\sin 	heta  rac{d}{d \cos 	heta} \left( \sin^2 	heta  rac{d P(\cos 	heta)}{d \cos 	heta} ight) + P(\cos 	heta) \left(A -  rac{m^2}{\sin^2 	heta} ight) &amp;= 0 \	 rac{d}{d \cos	heta} \left((1-\cos^2 	heta)  rac{d P(\cos 	heta)}{d \cos 	heta} ight) + P(\cos 	heta) \left( A -  rac{m^2}{1- \cos^2 	heta} ight) &amp;= 0 \	(1-\cos^2 	heta)  rac{d^2 P(\cos 	heta)}{d \cos 	heta^2} - 2 \cos 	heta  rac{d P(\cos 	heta)}{d 	heta} + P(\cos 	heta)\left(A -  rac{m^2}{1-\cos^2 	heta}ight)	\label{eq:change1}\end{align}\eqref{eq:change1} is a second order differential equation with non-constant coefficient. It has the form of the associated Legendre differential equation where we identify \( A = l(l+1) \) where $l$ is an integer. This solution impose \( 0 \le m \le l\). egin{equation}	\label{eq:leg}	P(\cos 	heta) = P_l^{|m|}(\cos 	heta)\end{equation}The spherical harmonicsWe can now use \eqref{eq:leg} and \eqref{eq:azisol} to write the general form of \( Y(	heta,\phi) \) egin{equation}	\label{eq:spheharm}	Y_l^m(	heta,\phi) = \alpha e^{im\phi}P_l^{|m|}(\cos	heta)\end{equation}\( Y_l^m(	heta,\phi) \) needs to be normalized, so we can find the value of \( \alpha \) using the orthonogonality of the associated Legendre polynomials. egin{align}	\int_0^{\pi} \int_0^{2\pi} Y_l^{m*}(	heta,\phi) Y_l^m(	heta,\phi) \sin 	heta d	heta d\phi &amp;= 1 \	\alpha^2 \int_0^{\pi} \int_0^{2\pi} e^{i(m-m)\phi} P_l^{|m|}(\cos 	heta) P_l^{|m|}(\cos 	heta) \sin 	heta d	heta d\phi&amp;= 1 \	\alpha^2 \left[\int_0^{2\pi} d\phiight] \left[\int_{0}^{\cos \pi} 	heta P_l^{|m|}(\cos 	heta) P_l^{|m|}(\cos	heta) \sin 	heta d	heta ight] &amp;= 1 \	\alpha^2  rac{4\pi(l+|m|)!}{(2l+1)(l-|m|)!} &amp;= 1 \	\alpha &amp;= \sqrt{ rac{2l+1}{4\pi} rac{(l-|m|)!}{(l+|m|)!}} \	\label{eq:spheharmnorm}\end{align}We now have a general formula for \( Y_l^m(	heta,\phi) \), which is called a spherical harmonic \eqref{eq:sphericalharmonic}. Due to the Legendre polynomials orthogonality, all the spherical harmonics are orthogonals. egin{equation}\label{eq:sphericalharmonic}Y_l^m(	heta,\phi) = \sqrt{ rac{2l+1}{4\pi} rac{(l-|m|)!}{(l+|m|)!}}e^{im\phi} P_l^{|m|}(\cos 	heta)\end{equation}In order to deal with purely real functions, it is common to use the real spherical harmonics which can be obtained by a simple linear combination of the complex spherical harmonics \eqref{eq:ctor} egin{equation}	\label{eq:ctor}		ilde{Y}_l^m =  egin{cases}  rac{(-1)^m}{\sqrt{2}} \left( Y_l^m + Y_l^{m\dagger} ight) &amp; \mbox{if } m &gt; 0 \					Y_l^m &amp; \mbox{if } m = 0 \					 rac{(-1)^m}{i\sqrt{2}} \left( Y_l^{m} - Y_l^{m\dagger} ight) &amp; \mbox{if } m &lt; 0 \end{cases} \end{equation}The radial equationThe radial equation is trickier to solve, first we need to plug the value of \( A \) found in \eqref{eq:change1}. egin{equation}	\label{eq:rad1}	 rac{d}{dr}\left( r^2  rac{dR(r)}{dr} ight) +  rac{2\mu r^2}{\hbar^2} \left(  rac{e^2}{4\pi \varepsilon_0 r} + E ight)R(r) - l(l+1)R(r) = 0\end{equation}We will now make a first change of variables, we will use a function \( u(r) \) such that \( R(r) =  rac{u(r)}{r} \). egin{align}
onumber	 rac{d}{dr} \left( r^2  rac{dR(r)}{dr} ight) &amp;=  rac{d}{dr} \left(r  rac{d u(r)}{dr} - u(r) ight) \
onumber							 &amp;=  rac{du(r)}{dr} -  rac{du(r)}{dr} + r rac{d^2u(r)}{dr^2} \\label{eq:rad2}							 &amp;= r rac{d^2 u(r)}{dr^2}\end{align}Using \eqref{eq:rad2} we can rewrite \eqref{eq:rad1} as \eqref{eq:rad3} and make some rearangements egin{align}	r  rac{d^2 u(r)}{dr^2} +  rac{2\mu}{\hbar^2} \left( rac{e^2}{4\pi\varepsilon_0 r} + E ight)ru(r) -  rac{l(l+1)}{r} u(r) &amp;= 0 \	- rac{\hbar^2}{2\mu} rac{d^2 u(r)}{dr^2} -  rac{e^2}{4\pi\varepsilon_0 r}u(r) - Eu(r) +  rac{\hbar^2}{2\mu}l(l+1)  rac{u(r)}{r^2} &amp;= 0 \ 	- rac{\hbar^2}{2\mu} rac{d^2 u(r)}{dr^2} + u(r) \left(- rac{e^2}{4\pi\varepsilon_0 r} +  rac{\hbar^2}{2\mu} rac{l(l+1)}{r^2}ight) &amp;= Eu(r) \	\label{eq:rad3}	- rac{\hbar^2}{2\mu E} rac{d^2 u(r)}{dr^2} + u(r) \left(- rac{e^2}{4\pi\varepsilon_0 r E} +  rac{\hbar^2}{2\mu E} rac{l(l+1)}{r^2}ight) &amp;= u(r) \end{align}It is now convenient to use a new variable \( k^2 = - rac{2\mu E}{\hbar^2} \), it will simplify the notation. \eqref{eq:rad3} is now \eqref{eq:rad4} egin{align}
onumber	 rac{1}{k^2} rac{d^2 u(r)}{dr^2} + u(r) \left(- rac{e^2}{4\pi\varepsilon_0 r E} -  rac{1}{k^2} rac{l(l+1)}{r^2}ight) &amp;= u(r) \\label{eq:rad4}	 rac{1}{k^2} rac{d^2 u(r)}{dr^2} &amp;= u(r) \left( rac{1}{k^2}  rac{l(l+1)}{r^2} + 1 -  rac{\mu e^2}{2\pi \varepsilon_0 \hbar^2 k}  rac{1}{kr} ight) \\end{align}It is time for a second change of variable, we will use \( ho = 2kr \), now \( u(r) \) is \( w(ho) \) and \( 2k dr = dho\). We will also introduce the quantity \( ho_0 =  rac{\mu e^2}{2\pi \varepsilon \hbar^2 k} \) which will again simplify the notation. We can rewrite \eqref{eq:rad4} as \eqref{eq:rad5}. egin{equation}\label{eq:rad5} rac{d^2 w(ho)}{d ho^2} = w(ho) \left( \color{#235FA4}{ rac{l(l+1)}{ho^2}} + \color{#FF4242}{ rac{1}{4}} -  rac{ho_0}{2ho} ight)\end{equation}As we still don’t know \( w(ho) \), we will take a look at its asymptotic behavior for small and large values of \( ho \) (\( ho ightarrow +\infty \) and \( ho ightarrow 0 \)).Limit at \( ho ightarrow + \infty \)For very large values of $ho$, only the red term of the parenthesis on the right hand side of \eqref{eq:rad5} does not vanish, we can rewrite. egin{equation}	\label{eq:rad6}	 rac{d^2 w_{\infty}(ho)}{dho^2} =  rac{1}{4}w_{\infty}(ho)\end{equation}\eqref{eq:rad6} is a second order differential equation with constant coefficients and has a simple solution \eqref{eq:rad7} where A and B are constants. egin{equation}	\label{eq:rad7}	w_{\infty}(ho) = A e^{ rac{1}{2}ho} + B e^{- rac{1}{2}ho}\end{equation}As our solution needs to be normalized we have to set \( A=0 \). We will also drop the $B$ for the moment and compute the normalization constant at the end. We now have our solution \eqref{eq:rad8} egin{equation}	\label{eq:rad8}	w_{\infty}(ho) = e^{- rac{1}{2}ho}\end{equation}Limit at $ho ightarrow 0$For very small values of $ho$, the blue term in the parenthesis of \eqref{eq:rad5} will dominate the other terms and we can rewrite the equation egin{equation